<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900626-0077</DOCNO><DOCID>900626-0077.</DOCID><HL>   Southern Co. Says   Dispute Settled   For $300 Million   ----   By Glenn Ruffenach   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>06/26/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15</SO><CO>   GSU SO</CO><IN>ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)</IN><LP>   ATLANTA -- Southern Co. said its subsidiaries will receiveabout $300 million, before taxes, in a settlement with GulfStates Utilities Co. over disputed power sales contracts.   Southern Co., the giant utility holding company, said theproposed settlement will be made in the form of a financialpackage, including cash, common stock and deferred payments.The company said it couldn't estimate the effect on earnings.</LP><TEXT>   Gulf States, based in Beaumont, Texas, said the settlementwas in the best interests of its shareholders. Thefour-year-old dispute &quot;was like a dark cloud hanging over us,preventing us from looking into the future,&quot; a spokeswomansaid.   Gulf States said its cash outlay would total $167 million.Of the remaining $133 million, $68 million is in an escrowaccount, and the balance will be paid in the form of sixmillion new shares of Gulf States common stock.   The spokeswoman for Gulf States said the company expectsto take an after-tax charge to net income of between $110million and $115 million in 1990. In 1989, Gulf States posteda loss of $45.5 million, or $1 a share, on revenue of $1.6billion.   The dispute began in July 1986. Gulf States, which hadcontracted to buy approximately $1 billion in electricityfrom Southern Co. over a 10-year period beginning in 1982,asked Southern Co. to consider renegotiating the contractsbecause energy demands had fallen below predicted levels.When Southern Co. declined, Gulf States filed suit in U.S.District Court in Beaumont. Southern Co. countersued inDecember 1988.   No hearings had been scheduled for the suits. Both caseswere still in discovery.   Southern Co.'s president, Edward L. Addison, said in astatement, &quot;We're pleased that we've been able to resolvethis contract dispute in out-of-court negotiations and cometo terms that protect the long-term interests of ourcompanies.&quot;   As collateral for future payments, Gulf States said itwill pledge the Lewis Creek Generating Plant, a 520-megawattgas-fired facility near Willis, Texas. Gulf States will alsoprovide Southern Co. with transmission access to the plant ata rate approved by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.   The settlement is subject to several contingencies,including approval by the Federal Energy RegulatoryCommission and the Securities and Exchange Commission.Southern Co. said the settlement will terminate the contractsand end litigation between the parties.</TEXT></DOC>